#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:5
msgid "CPU Isolation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:8
msgid "Introduction"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:10
msgid ""
"\"CPU Isolation\" means leaving a CPU exclusive to a given workload without "
"any undesired code interference from the kernel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:13
msgid ""
"Those interferences, commonly pointed out as \"noise\", can be triggered by "
"asynchronous events (interrupts, timers, scheduler preemption by workqueues "
"and kthreads, ...) or synchronous events (syscalls and page faults)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:18
msgid ""
"Such noise usually goes unnoticed. After all, synchronous events are a "
"component of the requested kernel service. And asynchronous events are "
"either sufficiently well-distributed by the scheduler when executed as tasks "
"or reasonably fast when executed as interrupt. The timer interrupt can even "
"execute 1024 times per seconds without a significant and measurable impact "
"most of the time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:25
msgid ""
"However some rare and extreme workloads can be quite sensitive to those "
"kinds of noise. This is the case, for example, with high bandwidth network "
"processing that can't afford losing a single packet or very low latency "
"network processing. Typically those use cases involve DPDK, bypassing the "
"kernel networking stack and performing direct access to the networking "
"device from userspace."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:32
msgid ""
"In order to run a CPU without or with limited kernel noise, the related "
"housekeeping work needs to be either shut down, migrated or offloaded."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:37
msgid "Housekeeping"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:39
msgid ""
"In the CPU isolation terminology, housekeeping is the work, often "
"asynchronous, that the kernel needs to process in order to maintain all its "
"services. It matches the noises and disturbances enumerated above except "
"when at least one CPU is isolated. Then housekeeping may make use of further "
"coping mechanisms if CPU-tied work must be offloaded."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:46
msgid ""
"Housekeeping CPUs are the non-isolated CPUs where the kernel noise is moved "
"away from isolated CPUs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:49
msgid ""
"The isolation can be implemented in several ways depending on the nature of "
"the noise:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:52
msgid ""
"Unbound work, where \"unbound\" means not tied to any CPU, can be simply "
"migrated away from isolated CPUs to housekeeping CPUs. This is the case of "
"unbound workqueues, kthreads and timers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:56
msgid ""
"Bound work, where \"bound\" means tied to a specific CPU, usually can't be "
"moved away as-is by nature. Either:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:59
msgid ""
"The work must switch to a locked implementation. E.g.: This is the case of "
"RCU with CONFIG_RCU_NOCB_CPU."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:62
msgid ""
"The related feature must be shut down and considered incompatible with "
"isolated CPUs. E.g.: Lockup watchdog, unreliable clocksources, etc..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:66
msgid ""
"An elaborate and heavyweight coping mechanism stands as a replacement. E.g.: "
"the timer tick is shut down on nohz_full CPUs but with the constraint of "
"running a single task on them. A significant cost penalty is added on kernel "
"entry/exit and a residual 1Hz scheduler tick is offloaded to housekeeping "
"CPUs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:73
msgid ""
"In any case, housekeeping work has to be handled, which is why there must be "
"at least one housekeeping CPU in the system, preferably more if the machine "
"runs a lot of CPUs. For example one per node on NUMA systems."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:78
msgid ""
"Also CPU isolation often means a tradeoff between noise-free isolated CPUs "
"and added overhead on housekeeping CPUs, sometimes even on isolated CPUs "
"entering the kernel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:83
msgid "Isolation features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:85
msgid ""
"Different levels of isolation can be configured in the kernel, each of which "
"has its own drawbacks and tradeoffs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:89
msgid "Scheduler domain isolation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:91
msgid ""
"This feature isolates a CPU from the scheduler topology. As a result, the "
"target isn't part of the load balancing. Tasks won't migrate either from or "
"to it unless affined explicitly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:95
msgid ""
"As a side effect the CPU is also isolated from unbound workqueues and "
"unbound kthreads."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:99
#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:146
msgid "Requirements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:101
msgid "CONFIG_CPUSETS=y for the cpusets-based interface"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:104
#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:167
msgid "Tradeoffs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:106
msgid ""
"By nature, the system load is overall less distributed since some CPUs are "
"extracted from the global load balancing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:110
#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:126
msgid "Interfaces"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:112
msgid ""
"Documentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v2.rst cpuset isolated partitions are "
"recommended because they are tunable at runtime."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:115
msgid ""
"The 'isolcpus=' kernel boot parameter with the 'domain' flag is a less "
"flexible alternative that doesn't allow for runtime reconfiguration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:120
msgid "IRQs isolation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:122
msgid ""
"Isolate the IRQs whenever possible, so that they don't fire on the target "
"CPUs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:128
msgid ""
"The file /proc/irq/\\*/smp_affinity as explained in detail in Documentation/"
"core-api/irq/irq-affinity.rst page."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:131
msgid "The \"irqaffinity=\" kernel boot parameter for a default setting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:133
msgid ""
"The \"managed_irq\" flag in the \"isolcpus=\" kernel boot parameter tries a "
"best effort affinity override for managed IRQs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:137
msgid "Full Dynticks (aka nohz_full)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:139
msgid ""
"Full dynticks extends the dynticks idle mode, which stops the tick when the "
"CPU is idle, to CPUs running a single task in userspace. That is, the timer "
"tick is stopped if the environment allows it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:143
msgid "Global timer callbacks are also isolated from the nohz_full CPUs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:148
msgid "CONFIG_NO_HZ_FULL=y"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:151
msgid "Constraints"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:153
msgid ""
"The isolated CPUs must run a single task only. Multitask requires the tick "
"to maintain preemption. This is usually fine since the workload usually "
"can't stand the latency of random context switches."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:157
msgid ""
"No call to the kernel from isolated CPUs, at the risk of triggering random "
"noise."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:160
msgid "No use of POSIX CPU timers on isolated CPUs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:162
msgid ""
"Architecture must have a stable and reliable clocksource (no unreliable TSC "
"that requires the watchdog)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:169
msgid ""
"In terms of cost, this is the most invasive isolation feature. It is assumed "
"to be used when the workload spends most of its time in userspace and "
"doesn't rely on the kernel except for preparatory work because:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:174
msgid ""
"RCU adds more overhead due to the locked, offloaded and threaded callbacks "
"processing (the same that would be obtained with \"rcu_nocbs\" boot "
"parameter)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:178
msgid ""
"Kernel entry/exit through syscalls, exceptions and IRQs are more costly due "
"to fully ordered RmW operations that maintain userspace as RCU extended "
"quiescent state. Also the CPU time is accounted on kernel boundaries instead "
"of periodically from the tick."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:183
msgid ""
"Housekeeping CPUs must run a 1Hz residual remote scheduler tick on behalf of "
"the isolated CPUs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:187
msgid "Checklist"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:189
msgid ""
"You have set up each of the above isolation features but you still observe "
"jitters that trash your workload? Make sure to check a few elements before "
"proceeding."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:193
msgid ""
"Some of these checklist items are similar to those of real-time workloads:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:196
msgid ""
"Use mlock() to prevent your pages from being swapped away. Page faults are "
"usually not compatible with jitter sensitive workloads."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:199
msgid ""
"Avoid SMT to prevent your hardware thread from being \"preempted\" by "
"another one."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:202
msgid ""
"CPU frequency changes may induce subtle sorts of jitter in a workload. "
"Cpufreq should be used and tuned with caution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:205
msgid ""
"Deep C-states may result in latency issues upon wake-up. If this happens to "
"be a problem, C-states can be limited via kernel boot parameters such as "
"processor.max_cstate or intel_idle.max_cstate. More finegrained tunings are "
"described in Documentation/admin-guide/pm/cpuidle.rst page"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:211
msgid ""
"Your system may be subject to firmware-originating interrupts - x86 has "
"System Management Interrupts (SMIs) for example. Check your system BIOS to "
"disable such interference, and with some luck your vendor will have a BIOS "
"tuning guidance for low-latency operations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:218
msgid "Full isolation example"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:220
msgid ""
"In this example, the system has 8 CPUs and the 8th is to be fully isolated. "
"Since CPUs start from 0, the 8th CPU is CPU 7."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:224
msgid "Kernel parameters"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:226
msgid ""
"Set the following kernel boot parameters to disable SMT and setup tick and "
"IRQ isolation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:229
msgid "Full dynticks: nohz_full=7"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:231
msgid "IRQs isolation: irqaffinity=0-6"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:233
msgid "Managed IRQs isolation: isolcpus=managed_irq,7"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:235
msgid "Prevent SMT: nosmt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:237
msgid "The full command line is then:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:239
msgid "nohz_full=7 irqaffinity=0-6 isolcpus=managed_irq,7 nosmt"
msgstr ""

