#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:338
msgid "Debugging"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:340
msgid ""
"Of course things are never so easy, especially on this matter. Chances are "
"that actual noise will be observed in the aforementioned trace.7 file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:344
msgid ""
"The best way to investigate further is to enable finer grained tracepoints "
"such as those of subsystems producing asynchronous events: workqueue, timer, "
"irq_vector, etc... It also can be interesting to enable the tick_stop event "
"to diagnose why the tick is retained when that happens."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:350
msgid "Some tools may also be useful for higher level analysis:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:352
msgid ""
"Documentation/tools/rtla/rtla.rst provides a suite of tools to analyze "
"latency and noise in the system. For example Documentation/tools/rtla/rtla-"
"osnoise.rst runs a kernel tracer that analyzes and output a summary of the "
"noises."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/cpu-isolation.rst:356
msgid ""
"dynticks-testing does something similar to rtla-osnoise but in userspace. It "
"is available at git://git.kernel.org/pub/scm/linux/kernel/git/frederic/"
"dynticks-testing.git"
msgstr ""
